{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493229","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493229"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:01:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:01:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1259"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1259"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.21,0.65,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1259"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53470"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1259"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1259"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38939"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"684"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4875"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14468"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15036"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42264"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53470"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 21-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of sore throat and fever. She is able to tolerate oral liquids. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C. Her pharynx is reddened with bilateral tonsillar exudates. She has bilateral anterior cervical lymphadenopathy. Her chest is clear on auscultation. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender, with fullness in the left upper quadrant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is prescribed amoxicillin for presumed bacterial pharyngitis. Four days later, she returns with a generalised, widespread maculopapular rash.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for her rash?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thrombocytopaenia secondary to splenomegaly","Hypersensitivity to amoxicillin","Drug-related reaction in the setting of a viral infection","Scarlet fever","Stevens-Johnson syndrome"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of acute pharyngitis, which can have either a viral or bacterial aetiology. The presence of fever, tonsillar exudates, and anterior cervical lymphadenopathy led to a provisional diagnosis of bacterial pharyngitis and treatment with amoxicillin. However, the subsequent development of a generalised maculopapular rash four days after starting antibiotics raises suspicion of a viral infection, particularly Epstein-Barr virus (EBV).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug-related reaction in the setting of a viral infection\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely explanation for her rash. This phenomenon is well-documented, particularly with amoxicillin use in undiagnosed EBV infections. The presence of left upper quadrant fullness, suggestive of mild splenomegaly, further supports the possibility of infectious mononucleosis due to EBV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypersensitivity to amoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely in this case. While it can present with a maculopapular rash, delayed hypersensitivity reactions typically occur after 7-10 days of treatment. Immediate hypersensitivity reactions (Type 1) would be expected within 1 hour of receiving a dose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombocytopaenia secondary to splenomegaly\u003C/strong\u003E would not typically present with a maculopapular rash. Instead, it would more likely cause petechiae or purpura. Additionally, there are no other key features of long-standing splenomegaly in this otherwise well patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScarlet fever\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by a fine, sandpaper-like rash, typically starting on the trunk and spreading to the extremities, often accompanied by a \u0027strawberry tongue\u0027. This presentation does not fit the clinical picture described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStevens-Johnson syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a severe mucocutaneous reaction, often triggered by medications, presenting with widespread skin detachment and mucosal involvement. The absence of mucosal involvement and the nature of the rash make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights the importance of considering viral infections, particularly EBV, in young adults presenting with pharyngitis. Rapid antigen testing for common bacterial agents can help guide treatment decisions. It\u0027s worth noting that amoxicillin is not the preferred antibiotic for treatment of bacterial pharyngitis due to the risk of drug-related reactions in the setting of undiagnosed EBV infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Widespread maculopapular rash following antibiotic use for a query bacterial infection may suggest a true viral infection leading to a drug-related reaction.","Timing for rash eruption in a delayed hypersensitivity to amoxicillin is expected to occur after day 7-10 of treatment.","Amoxicillin is not the preferred antibiotic for treatment of bacterial pharyngitis due to the risk of drug-related reactions in the setting of undiagnosed EBV infections."],"references":["Chahine E, Chamoun J, Sucher A. Management of Streptococcal Pharyngitis. In: Uspharmacist.com [online]. 2013; cited 1 January 2022. Available at: https://www.uspharmacist.com/article/management-of-streptococcal-pharyngitis","Solensky R. Penicillin allergy: delayed hypersensitivity reactions. In: UpToDate [online].  2021; cited 1 January 2022. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/penicillin-allergy-delayed-hypersensitivity-reactions","Davuluri S, Bansal P. Cryoglobulinemic vasculitis. In: Statpearls [online]. 2021; cited 1 January 2022. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK556045/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38939"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1259"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38939","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38939"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-21T18:54:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-21T18:56:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1259"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53470"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\